#### Why am I disinterested in incentives?

Incentives imply making decisions on behalf of others.  In the worlds I’m interested in, decisions are made by people affected by outcomes, with stake.  “A world in which many worlds fit”, to quote the New Zapatista movement (h/t [Marisol de la Cadena](https://www.marisoldelacadena.com/)). Related values:

> Suggest, but do not impose.

> Represent, but do not replace.

> Build, but do not ruin.

> Obey, but do not dictate.

> Descend to the people, but do not dominate.

> Persuade, but do not defeat.

> Serve the others, but not yourself.

> — *People Without Faces [(Source)](https://mobile.twitter.com/BlackSocialists/status/1348286392783282176)*

Regarding the benefits of incentives, they may create efficiences in measurable values — and yet, in the words of [Dee W Hock](https://www.deewhock.com/essays/community-and-the-non-monetary-exchange-of-value-1):

> It doesn't occur to us that efficiency is often ineffective; that we may be destroying an extremely effective system whose values we cannot measure in order to calculate the efficiency of ineffective systems.  It doesn't occur to us that attempting to engineer mechanistic societies and instituions based on mathematical measurement may be fundamentally flawed.  As the popular dictum declares, 'What gets measured is what egets done.' That is precisely the problem, for it requires that much more important values be ignored." (from [Community and the Exchange of Value](https://www.deewhock.com/essays/community-and-the-non-monetary-exchange-of-value-1))

#### Why am I disinterested in carbon credits, ecosystem services, and the financialization of nature and life?

These systems have been tried — and they don’t work.  See Naomi Klein’s *This Changes Everything* ([Summary](https://www.resilience.org/stories/2014-12-28/heft-notes-naomi-klein-s-this-changes-everything/), [Book and film](https://thischangeseverything.org/)).  From the summary on Resilience.org, by Paul Heft:

> Many large environmental organizations ("Big Green groups") have close ties to large polluting businesses. Many of these groups champion watered-down climate actions, such as "market-based" solutions, which do not aim for a full transition away from fossil fuels."The failure of this polite strategy is beyond debate." (200) Some have even supported fracking. Businesses have gamed the cap-and-trade system implemented in Europe; carbon offsets don’t work very well. ... In the farms and forests used for carbon "offsets," which allow pollution to occur elsewhere: "In order for multinational corporations to protect their freedom to pollute the atmosphere, peasants, farmers, and Indigenous people are losing their freedom to live and sustain themselves in peace. g

They perpetuate land grabs from Indigenous peoples and sustainable cultures.

They lead to wasteful and ineffective tree planting programs  —

<blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Forest restoration and forest-based carbon are alot more expensive than widely reported. There is tremendous waste. In this thread I will explain why, drawing on our new World Development paper, with some asides about program effectiveness and data transparency. <a href="https://t.co/9ecJuSkC1b">https://t.co/9ecJuSkC1b</a></p>&mdash; Forrest Fleischman (@ForrestFleisch1) <a href="https://twitter.com/ForrestFleisch1/status/1498427654466424835?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">February 28, 2022</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

 — in contrast to productive, evidence-based actions, like protecting Indigenous land sovereignty: cultures which have stewarded their lands for thousands of years up to today.

They do to our worlds what extraction does to our people.  They threaten the ability for a world to exist on its own, by extracting and poisoning its resources.  The world must then participate in the market economy — trees, forests, mangroves, soil, wildlife, long-lived subsistence cultures, working for credits and dollars — in order to survive.

This happens over and over again.  A place, an ecology, humans and more-than-human relatives, survive for time immemorial.  An extractive project (fossil fuel / mining / water dams / extractive renewables) poisons the land, water, and food.  Since our relatives can no longer live from the land, they now must choose whether they will participate in the extractive industry that destroys their way of life, or resist — and risk starvation, violence, and murder.

I have no interest in seeing this tragedy brought upon our worlds and more-than-human relatives.  I have no interest in a culture that invades a place — a place that is surviving and living well — and divides it into reductions of “trees” (which host wildlife), “wildlife” (which pollinate trees), “soil” (which ground trees), “water” (which keeps all alive), “people” (which carry water).  I have no interest in the claim that these agents must “earn money, or else…”  I have no interest in naive programs made without local context, which waste resources and opportunities.  I have no interest in land grabs.  I have no interest in endeavors that fail to learn from themselves, choosing blind ignorance for the chance of personal gain — a race to the bottom, a race to the end of all of our worlds.

#### Without ecosystem services and carbon credits, how can we protect and support the world we belong to?

What is the problem?  Is it that tress and wildlife aren’t earning dollars?  When has that ever been a problem?  (When has it ever been a problem for human cultures, in the last million years?)

One problem is extraction.  Cultures believing worlds belong to them.  “When they see open land, they only know how to take it.” (Jennifer Elise Foerster, [*Leaving Tulsa*](https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/57637/leaving-tulsa)).  A place is nothing more than resources and obstacles, on the way towards progress — as illustrated by the Futurama exhibit in the 1964’s World Fair, the most viewed exhibition in the world at that time (sponsored by General Motors):

