If we don’t come to understand that *we belong to the world*, there won’t be many worlds to belong to much longer.

#### How can we do that?  How can we transcend cultures of extraction?

Begin by respecting Indigenous rights.  In places where people and ecologies have not been subsumed in market economies, and continue to live as they have for millennia, we must respect sovereignty.  As long as these relatives of ours live, the lands and waters to which they belong will continue on — and we know it, because the lands and waters to which they belong are still alive to this day.

(This runs counter to colonial “conservation” practices, from benevolent-seeming organizations like World Wildlife Foundation and the 30x30 initiative, which, tragically, remove people and cultures from the places they have stewarded for millennia — failing to understand that there is a place to “conserve”, because the people of that place *live* conservation.  These practices also perpetuate the same paradigm of extraction — “the world belongs to us, so we can put the plants and animals in a park and remove people from the picture, because humans do not belong to that world — it belongs to us.”  Listen to more on this subject from [Mordecai Ogada](http://www.thesustainabilityagenda.com/podcast/episode-144-interview-with-kenyan-conservationist-dr-mordecai-ogada-on-conservation-trends-in-kenya/) and this [short video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jOjAtHw94gI&feature=emb_title).)

In places where extraction has already begun, support *alternatives to extraction*, which can provide income for people who have seen their ways of life threatened, without extracting from the place in the process.  What can that look like?

- [Local filmmaking and media production](https://rebrand.ly/with-place).  Stewarded lands and cultures are some of the most beautiful places in our world — and we pay to see them, in all of our media.  What do you think provides better local incomes — raw material/resource extraction, or local film and media jobs?  Organizations like [If Not Us Then Who](https://ifnotusthenwho.me/) have shown that Indigenous filmmaking crews can earn 10x the income of jobs in extractive industries, in harmony with a place (as they always have).  The more vibrant and flourishing a place, the more we want to see it — in nature documentaries, in films and TV shows, in music videos, in digital media shorts and infotainment.  This means people can subsist from the beauty and wonders of a place, and belong to it, stewarding it for their survival and prosperity.

- Local science and research.  Where there is biodiversity, there are biological miracles – which can help us live better, offer medicines and therapies, and teach us about our worlds.  Pharmaceutical companies once sourced innovative therapies from Indigenous lands — acts known as “biopiracy”, which stopped due to court cases )the pharmaceuticals moved back to laboratories). And yet, the miracles of biodiversity and biology that the pharmaceuticals sought, are still around the world.  Research institutions, public health organizations, schools and academics, and those very same pharmaceutical companies — would they pay for research and samples from these places?  If so, what if that research could be produced by local peoples?  What do you think would offer better local incomes — raw material/resource extraction, or local research jobs?  The more vitality and diversity in a place, the more biological insights it holds, and the more we want them.  This means people can live in a mutualistic relationship with more-than-human relatives in a place, as cultures have lived for thousands of years.

- Agroecological Forestry.  There are ways to give energy to a place, and accept gifts in return — fruits, vegetables, seeds, saps, medicines.  Unlike industrial monoculture and cattle ranches, practices like agroecological forestry can actually *support* biodiversity in a place.  How wonderful, that as a place gives more gifts, it can benefit as well.  What do you think offers better local incomes — raw material/resource extraction, or community forestry and agroecology?  This means that people can subsist from the lands and fruit of a place, belonging to it, as people have lived for almost all of human history.

> (Do you have ideas for other alternatives to extraction?  Other ways that people can belong to places, and live in mutualistic relationships, even after places have been subsumed into market economies?  Share suggestions and the possibilities you see!)

In the short-term, all of these alternatives — local filmmaking and media, local scientific research, agroecological forestry — may require more support and investment than is required for short-term extraction.  At the same time, there are many forms of non-extractive and mutualistic exchange that can facilitate these capacity-building resources.  For example, buying media, medicinal samples, forest produce, in advance at a discount — providing resources to start these initiatives, providing benefits to customers, and creating mutualistic bonds between producers and customers.  After the up-front capacity is established, that capacity will be available for generations, supporting ways of life — even in a market economy — in which we can live in harmony with and belong to our worlds.

#### Are there ways to transcend extraction, and belong to our worlds, in industrialized places?

When we buy foods from the frontlines of extraction — non-local meat, crops, delicacies — we accelerate extraction.  When we buy oil from the frontlines of extraction — pipelines and wells on Indigenous and native lands, in our own countries and abroad — we accelerate the poisoning of our worlds.  When we burn gasoline to move 2,000 pound vehicles and heat our homes, we accelerate the heating of our atmosphere and the destruction our relatives are experiencing. 

Belonging to world means that our worlds aren’t ours for the taking.  If we wish to transcend extraction, and live in worlds that make sense — worlds that are resilient, worlds that survive, worlds that flourish — we must learn that more is less, and less is more.  Possessions don’t bring meaning, fulfillment, or wellbeing.   We learn this again and again and again.  The fast food and delivery is never as fulfilling as our home-cooked meals.  They still leave us with the discomfort, the restlessness, in the pit of our stomachs.  We buy more, eat more, drink more, consume more, watch more, numb ourselves more to fill the pit — but it only temporarily satisfies, and the pit grows deeper.  We work more to afford the lifestyles of numbness, to afford these lifestyles for our children and dependents, and that inner unsettled feeling never goes away.  That becomes our hollow not-life on this miracle of a planet, numb to our gifts from the sun, and waters, and wind, and sky, and biology, and our interconnected universe, every day.

Our lives are groundless — always shifting, always changing, never in our grasp.  When we’re hungry, or thirsty, or feeling a moment’s anxiety — we can act on that impulse, to find ground (a false, short-lived ground),  or we can sit with that feeling, and understand that life is groundless, and accept discomfort. 

> What happens with you when you begin to feel uneasy, unsettled, queasy? Notice the panic, notice when you instantly grab for something.

> — (Pema Chodron, [*When Things Fall Apart*](https://pennbookcenter.com/pema-chodron-when-things-fall-apart-quotes/))

We can leave off the television.  We can forget about the phone.  We can sit around the table — gathering, love, family, relations of unending varieties, in unending combinations.  We can transcend our idol worship of products and goods, as David Foster Wallace showed us.

>  In the day-to-day trenches of adult life, there is actually no such thing as atheism. There is no such thing as not worshipping. Everybody worships. The only choice we get is what to worship. And the compelling reason for maybe choosing some sort of god or spiritual-type thing to worship–be it JC or Allah, be it YHWH or the Wiccan Mother Goddess, or the Four Noble Truths, or some inviolable set of ethical principles–is that pretty much anything else you worship will eat you alive. If you worship money and things, if they are where you tap real meaning in life, then you will never have enough, never feel you have enough. It’s the truth. Worship your body and beauty and sexual allure and you will always feel ugly. And when time and age start showing, you will die a million deaths before they finally grieve you. On one level, we all know this stuff already. It’s been codified as myths, proverbs, clichés, epigrams, parables; the skeleton of every great story. The whole trick is keeping the truth up front in daily consciousness.

> Worship power, you will end up feeling weak and afraid, and you will need ever more power over others to numb you to your own fear. Worship your intellect, being seen as smart, you will end up feeling stupid, a fraud, always on the verge of being found out. But the insidious thing about these forms of worship is not that they’re evil or sinful, it’s that they’re unconscious. They are default settings.

> They’re the kind of worship you just gradually slip into, day after day, getting more and more selective about what you see and how you measure value without ever being fully aware that that’s what you’re doing.

> And the so-called real world will not discourage you from operating on your default settings, because the so-called real world of men and money and power hums merrily along in a pool of fear and anger and frustration and craving and worship of self. Our own present culture has harnessed these forces in ways that have yielded extraordinary wealth and comfort and personal freedom. The freedom all to be lords of our tiny skull-sized kingdoms, alone at the centre of all creation. This kind of freedom has much to recommend it. But of course there are all different kinds of freedom, and the kind that is most precious you will not hear much talk about much in the great outside world of wanting and achieving…. The really important kind of freedom involves attention and awareness and discipline, and being able truly to care about other people and to sacrifice for them over and over in myriad petty, unsexy ways every day.

> That is real freedom. That is being educated, and understanding how to think. The alternative is unconsciousness, the default setting, the rat race, the constant gnawing sense of having had, and lost, some infinite thing.

> I know that this stuff probably doesn’t sound fun and breezy or grandly inspirational the way a commencement speech is supposed to sound. What it is, as far as I can see, is the capital-T Truth, with a whole lot of rhetorical niceties stripped away. You are, of course, free to think of it whatever you wish. But please don’t just dismiss it as just some finger-wagging Dr Laura sermon. None of this stuff is really about morality or religion or dogma or big fancy questions of life after death.

> The capital-T Truth is about life BEFORE death.

> It is about the real value of a real education, which has almost nothing to do with knowledge, and everything to do with simple awareness; awareness of what is so real and essential, so hidden in plain sight all around us, all the time, that we have to keep reminding ourselves over and over:

> “This is water.”

> “This is water.”

> It is unimaginably hard to do this, to stay conscious and alive in the adult world day in and day out. Which means yet another grand cliché turns out to be true: your education really IS the job of a lifetime. And it commences: now.

> I wish you way more than luck.

> — David Foster Wallace, [Kenyon Commencement Address](https://web.ics.purdue.edu/~drkelly/DFWKenyonAddress2005.pdf) (May 21st, 2005).  [Audio link](https://soundcloud.com/wholesum/this-is-water-by-david-foster).

We can live our lives in ways that matter to us, and we can explore how to get on with less.  A lot less.

#### In practice, what does that mean?

- Food.  Buy local and organic where you can — and save the forest of microorganisms in your stomach from poison pesticides.  For the most local, organic, trustworthy, and healthy food, make it yourself!  You can garden with native edibles in your yard/community — and even easier, you can sprout seeds in jars in your kitchen.  One tablespoon of sprouting seeds, can grow into a jar of highly nutritious food in days.  We can become the producers, the chefs, the architects, and the gatherers, of our own food traditions.

- Meat.  The cheaper the meat, the worse our relative was treated and the worse it is for you.  That microorganism forest in your belly regulates the quality of your life — when you eat cheap meat (from fast food spots, casual restaurants, any place that doesn’t advertise organic and local sources), you’re eating a whole bunch of unprescribed antibiotics — and harming a critical part of yourself and your life experiences.    
If you want meat from our more-than-human kin, buy local, pasture-raised or free-range, organic, antibiotic-free meat, and prepare it at home.  It tastes better, saves you money, supports our four-legged relatives, supports the microorganism forests in our bellies, and supports the regeneration of the worlds we belong to.

- Heating/cooling.  Heat bodies, not spaces.  You can change the clothes you wear and adjust your immediate environment — hot water bottles, blankets, cold bottles, foamboard insulation on your walls — to save the hassle of fiddling with the temperature and save energy on the monthly bills.

- Transportation.  Discover public transportation networks and other ways to get around.  Trains.  Buses.  Bike routes.  Hidden paths and walkways.  With possibilities like remote work, find ways to live more locally.  End the car trips.  Bike day every day.  Travel and getaways close to home (saving yourself the hassle and discomfort of airports).  Take it easy, live local, and discover the worlds around us.

#### Will it really make a difference if I do these things?

_Much of this section is inspired by Karen O’Brien’s [*You Matter More Than You Think*](https://youmattermorethanyouthink.com), Donna Haraway’s [Staying With The Trouble*](https://www.dukeupress.edu/staying-with-the-trouble), Dr. Kim TallBear’s lectures on “Making Love and Relations” (below), and a recent conversation with a friend._

Who are you?  

… Are you *you* — just you, alone, in the universe?  Are you part of me?  Are the waters we drink from, which fill 70% of our bodies, part of us?  Are we part of the waters that fill 70% of our world?  Are we bodies with microorganism forests in our stomachs?  Are we microorganism forests with bodies around us?

In physics, light energy can be a wave, a particle, and a wave and a particle.  Can we be an individual, collectives, and an individual and collectives?  In physics, particles can be entangled at a distance.  Has there ever been a time when you’re thinking of a person — and suddenly, for the first time in a long time, your phone buzzes and it’s that person on the other end?

Are I/we connected in ways greater than we may realize?  Religions, science, cultural wisdom all teach us this — our connection.  In the Lakota language, a word commonly used to mean “sacred” — and interpreted by Christian missionaries as “God” — actually means **relations**, according to Albert White Hat (via [Dr. Kim TallBear](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zfdo2ujRUv8&t=2876s)):

