If we are entangled, connected, part of one another in these ways — when I/we act, it affects all of us.  Likewise, there are ways that I/we can be more purposeful and impactful about involving our communities in the worlds we’re creating — collective action, becoming together, is magnitudes more impactful than acting as in isolation.

(Research like [*Powers of 10*](https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/ab9ed0) shows that action at the village, township, municipality, county, community scales, is some our most impactful scales of action.

#### So how can we act as community, when people feel distant and isolated as ever?

Visit with neighbors.  Ask them questions.  Listen.  Re-connect.

Find the people you know — as well as the friends you haven’t met yet — and explore actions together, like chalking crosswalks at an intersection, or ordering sprouting seeds for our kitchens, or organizing a gathering/party/festival in the neighborhood.  Gather community — families, students, adults, businesses — and imagine ways we can get on with life on foot, bike, and wheels, free of the 2,000 vehicular cages.  How we can live more with each other.

Mainly, just start.

We can start by knocking on a neighbors door for a catch up.  Asking someone how they’re doing — listening, being there, being together.  Asking someone for help!

We can also start by [showing up](https://juststart.do) to a local event, meeting, gathering.  Trying something new.  Taking a risk.

And … just, starting.

#### So … just, start?

Just start.  Start making worlds.  Worlds of many worlds — where we, as places and cultures and relations, can make our own decisions and find our own ways to survive and thrive and belong to the world.  Where we support Indigenous land sovereignty and alternatives to extraction in frontline communities.  Where we live alternatives to extraction in our interconnected world — using less, releasing ground, finding life, living more — and doing it as community, always as community, in our entangled I/we/worlds.  

We are each other — biologically and as neighbors, humanly and as more-than-human relatives, waterly and as water carriers, humans with gut forests and gut forests with humans — and as communities and families that belong to our worlds and places and cultures together.  Just start living it.

